Comment: This is EXTREMELY inaccurate. US Airways 1549 occurred January 15 2009. The planes in the beginning are not from 2009. United Airlines DID NOT have the globe livery until 2010 when they (unfortunately) merged with Continental airlines. These two United planes should have continental written on the side of it. Yes they did fix this in the movie, BUT IT WAS STILL WRONG! Continental never had any ERJ 170s! They labeled the plane in the movie, Continental Connection, but continental connection only had a fleet of ATR‚Äôs and Q400‚Äôs (which one had been involved in Colgan Air 3407 [N200WQ]). The second huge mistake was also the American Airlines planes. THE LIVERY THEY WERE WEARING WAS FROM 2013-PRESENT! In 2009 they still wore the Chrome Livery of the silver paint! Everything at LaGuardia is screwed up in the movie. They somehow got the delta planes correct. (Except back then Delta Airlines was going through new livery repaints since 2008. So it would be unrealistic to see no Delta Airlines 2000s colors in the ‚ÄúDeltaflot‚Äù livery. They could have done a MUCH better job with this movie.

Title: Sully - Official Trailer [HD]
Comment: This is a very realistic recreation of the "miracle on the Hudson" plane "crash" and Tom Hanks' portrayal of Captain Chesley "Sully" Sullenberger is probably one of the best parts I've ever seen him play due to his uncanny resemblance to the real hero pilot of that incident.  Much of the plot of the film revolves around the NTSB investigators suggesting that Sully was not a good pilot because he decided to splash down in the Hudson instead of turning around for a landing back at LaGuardia airport or flying over the Teterboro airport in New Jersey.  Such a ruling would have forced him to take early retirement and lose his license to fly commercial airliners. They had computer simulations that "proved" that such an emergency landing could be easily done assuming he had a partially functional left engine.  Things looked bad for Scully for a while, but then some facts emerged that the NTSB had been conveniently concealing.  I don't want to spoil this excellent film by revealing them.  But, I'll just say this.  If you are ever on a airliner when all of the engines fail at once, you'll be glad to have Scully at the controls!

Title: Sully - Official Trailer [HD]
Comment:
You know its interesting that they are making MORE out of this then there was...

FAA NEVER went after him saying he could have landed at another airport.   They did simulator testing on that and found,  nearly 50% of the time IF the pilot KNEW what was going on, expected the twin engine failure, and diverted RIGHT after impact they could land at another airfield.   The difference though was 23 seconds.  IF the pilot did ANYTHING including follow a check list and/or try a restart, or anything else.   that was it...  they could not do it.

There was also NEVER a suggestion that one of the engines was still running.   the black boxes showed that right off the bat.

infact 1 thing sully did right away, was a make or break choice that ONLY 20% of tested pilots did.  Without going to the checklist, he immediately turned on his APU.  this one kept his radios and computers going.   

face it they are over-dramatizing.

The man was a hero.  Plain and simple.

This actually looks surprisingly technically correct.

T/O rwy 04 like they did for the actual flight, proper A320 aircraft and flight deck, EPR and N1 rollback with the birdstrikes, First Officer ND/PFD fail after dual engine shutdown, Tom Hanks starting the APU during that cockpit wide view scene, all the caution/warnings and memos on the ECAM, the FAA being dicks.....high hopes for authenticity.

Title: Sully - Official Trailer [HD]
Comment: 0:19 - the livery on the American Eagle/Envoy regional jet on the left side of the U.S. Airways A320 is American's new livery that was officially revealed by American on January 17th, 2013 (the first aircraft in the new livery being N908NN), whereas the movie chronicles the events of January 15th, 2009. Again at 0:30, we see an American Airlines Boeing 737-823 on the left side of the frame in the new American livery and we also see a United Airlines 737-700 with split scimitar winglets, which weren't installed on 737's until late 2013 and United debuted them on a 737-800 of theirs on Tuesday, February 18th, 2014 on flight 1273 from IAH to LAX. Otherwise, this trailer looks great!
